# Codex Adversarial Review

Target: branch diff against a63b2bb84240cd0c9602fcc865a252189e5a2683
Verdict: needs-attention

No-ship: the archive path can produce an unrecoverable or falsely successful OpenClaw retirement under realistic cutover failures.

Findings:
- [critical] Wrong-recipient archive is accepted as recoverable (runtime/deploy/archive-openclaw.sh:280-323)
  The script encrypts to whatever key is present at $PUBKEY, shreds the raw tarball, then validates by trying to decrypt with a newly generated bogus key and expecting failure. That does not prove Santiago can decrypt it; any valid but wrong recipient key will also reject the bogus identity with "no identity matched" and the script will report success. Impact: the only rollback archive can be permanently undecryptable after OpenClaw is retired.
  Recommendation: Replace the bogus-identity check with a real recoverability proof: verify a pinned known-good pubkey fingerprint before encryption and/or require an actual decrypt round-trip with Santiago's private key before shredding the raw tarball and appending the manifest row.
- [high] User-systemd errors are treated as safe inactive states (runtime/deploy/archive-openclaw.sh:226-245)
  Both systemctl --user probes are inside simple if statements, so any failure to connect to the user bus via su - ilsantino is interpreted as "already stopped" or "already disabled". The later pgrep only catches a currently running process; it does not prove the unit was disabled. Inference: on VPS/user-systemd setups where XDG_RUNTIME_DIR or the user manager is unavailable to su, OpenClaw can remain enabled and restart after login/reboot, racing the v2 daemon on the same control surface.
  Recommendation: Handle systemctl exit codes explicitly and fail on bus/manager errors. Invoke the user manager with an explicit runtime dir or machinectl/runuser pattern, then verify the unit is inactive and disabled/masked after the stop/disable operations.
- [high] Same-day sentinel can freeze a partial archive as success (runtime/deploy/archive-openclaw.sh:216-221)
  The idempotency check skips when any matching .age file exists for today. A prior run can create ENCRYPTED_PATH and then fail later in header validation, bogus-key probing, or manifest append. A retry without --force-new-archive then exits 0 before repairing or replacing that unverified archive, leaving operators with a false successful state.
  Recommendation: Write archives to a .partial/.tmp name excluded from the sentinel, validate recoverability, append the manifest, then atomically rename to the final .age name. Make the sentinel require a valid manifest row or revalidate the existing archive before skipping.

Next steps:
- Fix recoverability validation before cutover use.
- Make OpenClaw stop/disable verification fail closed on user-systemd errors.
- Make archive publication atomic so idempotent retries cannot bless partial output.
